projectInfo.name: Refugee Site Mapping Kakuma - Kenya (Zones 2-3)
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Kenyan government in facing the challenges associated with this influx of refugees. Among other things, the UNHCR manages the establishment of refugee settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid.
UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map several camps that do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads.
projectInfo.description:
Kakuma refugee camp is located in the northwestern region of Kenya. The camp was established in 1992 after the arrival of the "lost boys from Sudan". During this year, important Ethiopian refugee groups were succeeded in place of the Ethiopian government. Somalia has also experienced great insecurity and civil problems caused by the flight of the population.
CartONG has been supporting the WASH team of UNHCR for 3 years as part of the WASH KAP survey process - Knowledge, Attitudes, Practices on the issues of Water, Hygiene & Sanitation.
Mapping refugee camps helps the survey planning and sampling, analyzing the survey results, taking into account the spatial context and the exact location of the WASH infrastructure. This approach helps improving the global access of refugees to long-term water, sanitation and hygiene services.

CartONG has been working with UNHCR for several years on mapping and information management, helping them to map camps and carry out surveys that serve to improve the living conditions of refugees.

**Please watch [this video feedback of Sani, UNCHR WASH officer](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H6lf1FJYWTk), about a similar project implemented with CartONG in Congo. You can also read more information on [this news on our website](https://cartong.org/news/displaying-wash-infrastructure-household-survey-results-same-map).**
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Imagery ============ For this project, we will be using **Maxar Premium** Imagery --- 2. Buildings ============ * **Be as precise as possible!** _Zoom to distinguish the buildings. Draw the building in its entirety even if it could be partially covered by trees._ ##**How?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use the tool **area** to draw the buildings 2. Once it's drawn, open the menu on the left of your page and click on the "Building Features" category, then select **"buildings"** (this is the most generic building type, we do not know a more detailed building use because we are just using satellite imagery) 3. Finally, correct the angles and square your buildings by pressing down on the **"S"** key ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With editor JOSM:* 1. Use **Draw nodes** tool to draw the buildings, or the **buildings_tools** plug-in 2. Then draw the buildings and add the **building=yes** tag 3. Then, if you use the "draw nodes" tool, think to correct the angles and square the building by pressing **"Q"** key. `Warning: many buildings are very close to each other but do not touch each other. Try to draw them close to each other without connecting or sharing nodes between other buildings, roads or residential/natural areas. In ID Editor, you can avoid having nodes stick to each other by pressing the "Alt" key.` --- 3. Roads network ============ * **Please draw roads that are clearly visible** * **Connect the roads to the existing network** as much as possible. * **Avoid mapping very short roads that do not go anywhere** * **While drawing a road, you may cross your boundary square by a bit** in order to let the person who will draw the square next to yours connect his roads to the existing network. `The classification of roads in Africa is different from Western countries. How roads appear in African countries are not always representative of their economic and social role. In OSM, the typology of roads is based on the importance of roads and not on the type of surface material or their visual appearance. The road classifications proposed in OSM for African countries is based on the mapping experiences of many of these countries, as well as many conversations and discussions, it is more adapted to the context of this continent. ` ##**For this project, we will use the following categories :** **Minor/unclassified road (unclassified) :** For roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could pass and connect small villages or hamlet. **Path :** For small roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could not pass, but can be used by people on foot or on a two-wheeled vehicle. These roads can connect either uninhabited places or lead to cultivated fields. Only trace major roads that connect to populated places or other roads. **Track :** For smaller roads that are generally used for agricultural or forestry purposes. ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use the **line** tool to draw the roads 2. Once you have drawn a road, go to the menu on the left, find the category that corresponds to the classification of the road or the path (see definition above) *With JOSM:* 1. Use the **Draw nodes** tool to draw roads and paths 2. Draw the road and add the tag corresponding to its classification. **Highway=Unclassified** or **Highway=path** or **Highway=track** (cf. definition above) --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain permanently in the OSM database and visible and reusable by all. Be as accurate as possible! **Quality is more important than quantity!** Remember that mapping requires patience, attention and care.

**If you have questions, please ask in the comment section, one of our validators will be happy to answer!**
